        "kind": "pull_request",
        "title": "fix(install): harden stdin consumers to prevent pipe corruption in curl | bash",
        "body": "## Problem\n\nWhen invoked via `curl -fsSL https://openclaw.ai/install.sh | bash`, bash reads the script from stdin. Non-interactive subprocesses (npm, openclaw daemon, openclaw plugins) inherit stdin and can consume bytes from the script stream, causing truncated function names and hangs.\n\nPR #82918 attempted to fix this with a top-level pipe guard, but was [closed by steipete](https://github.com/openclaw/openclaw/pull/82918#issuecomment-4568506465) because the detection heuristic (`BASH_SOURCE[0]` + `/dev/stdin` pipe check) was too broad and fired in `bash -c` and other non-piped modes.\n\n## Fix\n\nFollow steipete's guidance: harden the actual stdin consumers instead of adding a global guard.\n\n- **Non-interactive subprocesses** (`npm install`, `openclaw daemon restart`, `openclaw plugins update`, `openclaw dashboard`): redirect stdin from `/dev/null` so they cannot consume script bytes.\n- **Interactive commands** (`openclaw onboard` in bootstrap): redirect stdin from `/dev/tty` so the onboarding process gets terminal input instead of the script stream.\n- **Wrapper functions** (`run_with_spinner`, `run_quiet_step`): add `< /dev/null` to fallback paths where raw commands run without gum's stdin protection.\n\nInteractive prompts (`prompt_choice`, `gum choose`, `openclaw doctor`, final `exec openclaw onboard`) already use `/dev/tty` and are unchanged.\n\nThis approach has no detection heuristics, no re-execution, and no behavior change for direct execution (`bash install.sh`). Each subprocess simply gets the correct stdin for its purpose.\n\nFixes #73814\n\n## Real behavior proof\n\n- Behavior or issue addressed: non-interactive subprocesses in install.sh can steal stdin bytes when the script is piped via `curl | bash`, causing truncated function names and hangs.\n- Real environment tested: macOS, bash 3.2 and 5.2, Node v24.2.0, openclaw main at latest.\n- Exact steps or command run after this patch:\n\n  ```bash\n  # Piped dry-run (simulates curl | bash)\n  cat scripts/install.sh | bash -s -- --dry-run --install-method npm\n\n  # Direct dry-run (simulates bash install.sh)\n  bash scripts/install.sh --dry-run --install-method npm\n\n  # Verify subprocess stdin is isolated\n  bash -c 'read -t 0.1 line; echo \"got: ${#line} chars\"' < /dev/null\n  # Output: got: 0 chars\n  ```\n\n- Evidence after fix (terminal output):\n\n  ```\n  === Piped dry-run (simulates curl | bash) ===\n  Dry run: yes\n  ✓ Dry run complete (no changes made)\n  === Direct dry-run (simulates bash install.sh) ===\n  Dry run: yes\n  ✓ Dry run complete (no changes made)\n  ```\n\n- Observed result after fix: both piped and direct modes complete without truncation errors. Subprocesses receive `/dev/null` as stdin and cannot consume the script stream.\n- What was not tested: full npm install in piped mode (requires clean environment); WSL2 reproduction of the original truncation. The fix is mechanical (`< /dev/null` redirections) and does not depend on platform-specific behavior.\n",
        "branch": "fix/install-stdin-tty-safety",
